    "title": {
        "rendered": "Link control"
    },
    "content": {
        "rendered": "\n<p class=\"has-text-align-right has-small-font-size\"><a href=\"https://wordpress.org/documentation/article/blocks/\">Go to the list of blocks</a></p>\n\n\n\n<p>Use the links control to change how links are supposed to behave when interacting with the block editor.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>First, you need to add a block with a hyperlink \u2014 a good example is the <a href=\"https://wordpress.org/documentation/article/paragraph-block/\">paragraph block</a>.</p>\n\n\n\n<p class=\"has-background\" style=\"background-color:#e5f5fa\">Refer to this article for&nbsp;<a href=\"https://wordpress.org/documentation/article/adding-a-new-block/\">detailed instructions on adding blocks</a>.</p>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Adding links</h2>\n\n\n\n<p>First, insert a hyperlink with the link icon. You can also use the <kbd>Ctrl+K</kbd> (or <kbd>\u2318+K</kbd>) keyboard shortcut.</p>\n\n\n\n<p>Clicking on the link icon will open a dialog box. </p>\n\n\n\n<p>You can type in the URL of the page you want to link to. </p>\n\n\n\n<p>You can also use the Search text box to search for pages on your own website. If you start typing a keyword into the Search text box, WordPress will list content titles on your website that match the keyword. This is helpful for on-site link building.</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-video\"><video controls src=\"https://wordpress.org/documentation/files/2023/08/link-control-6.7.mp4\"></video></figure>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>Tip:&nbsp;</strong>If you already have the URL of the website you want to link to in the clipboard, highlight the text, you want to make into a link and use <kbd>Ctrl+V</kbd> (or <kbd>\u2318+V</kbd>) to add the hyperlink to the text.</p>\n\n\n\n<h2 class=\"wp-block-heading\">Open location</h2>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image aligncenter size-full is-resized\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"877\" height=\"809\" src=\"https://wordpress.org/documentation/files/2024/01/image-7.png\" alt=\"Example of how to open the link on a new tab.\" class=\"wp-image-16359522\" style=\"width:628px;height:auto\" srcset=\"https://wordpress.org/documentation/files/2024/01/image-7.png 877w, https://wordpress.org/documentation/files/2024/01/image-7-300x277.png 300w, https://wordpress.org/documentation/files/2024/01/image-7-768x708.png 768w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 877px) 100vw, 877px\" /></figure>\n\n\n\n<p>The <strong>Open in new tab</strong> toggle switch allows you to control where the new page should open. By default, the switch is set to <strong>off</strong>.</p>\n\n\n\n<ul class=\"wp-block-list\">\n<li><strong>off</strong>&nbsp;opens in the same browser tab</li>\n\n\n\n<li><strong>on</strong>&nbsp;opens in a new browser tab</li>\n</ul>\n\n\n\n<p>This toggle option is also available when you open the link editing panel. Open the <strong>Advanced </strong>menu and you will see the same toggle switch as well as the <strong>nofollow</strong> option.</p>\n\n\n\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image aligncenter size-full is-resized\"><img loading=\"lazy\" decoding=\"async\" width=\"861\" height=\"824\" src=\"https://wordpress.org/documentation/files/2024/01/image-8.png\" alt=\"Link editing panel with the advanced options displayed\" class=\"wp-image-16359524\" style=\"width:519px;height:auto\" srcset=\"https://wordpress.org/documentation/files/2024/01/image-8.png 861w, https://wordpress.org/documentation/files/2024/01/image-8-300x287.png 300w, https://wordpress.org/documentation/files/2024/01/image-8-768x735.png 768w\" sizes=\"auto, (max-width: 861px) 100vw, 861px\" /></figure>\n",
        "protected": false
    },
    "excerpt": {
        "rendered": "<p>This page explains how you can use the links control in WordPress to change how links behave when interacting with the block editor.</p>\n",
        "protected": false
    },
